# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: azure-cdn
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In computing, a **cache** (/kæʃ/ ⓘ *KASH*) is a hardware or software component that stores data so that future requests for that data can be served faster; the data stored in a cache might be the result of an earlier computation or a copy of data stored elsewhere.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A **cache hit** occurs when the requested data can be found in a cache, while a **cache miss** occurs when it cannot.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Cache hits are served by reading data from the cache, which is faster than recomputing a result or reading from a slower data store; thus, the more requests that can be served from the cache, the faster the system performs.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] To be cost-effective, caches must be relatively small.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Nevertheless, caches are effective in many areas of computing because typical computer applications access data with a high degree of locality of reference.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Such access patterns exhibit temporal locality, where data is requested that has been recently requested, and spatial locality, where data is requested that is stored near data that has already been requested.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In memory design, there is an inherent trade-off between capacity and speed because larger capacity implies larger size and thus greater physical distances for signals to travel causing propagation delays.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] There is also a tradeoff between high-performance technologies such as SRAM and cheaper, easily mass-produced commodities such as DRAM, flash, or hard disks.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The buffering provided by a cache benefits one or both of latency and throughput (bandwidth).
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A larger resource incurs a significant latency for access – e.g. it can take hundreds of clock cycles for a modern 4 GHz processor to reach DRAM.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] This is mitigated by reading large chunks into the cache, in the hope that subsequent reads will be from nearby locations and can be read from the cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Prediction or explicit prefetching can be used to guess where future reads will come from and make requests ahead of time; if done optimally, the latency is bypassed altogether.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The use of a cache also allows for higher throughput from the underlying resource, by assembling multiple fine-grain transfers into larger, more efficient requests.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In the case of DRAM circuits, the additional throughput may be gained by using a wider data bus.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Hardware implements cache as a block of memory for temporary storage of data likely to be used again.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Central processing units (CPUs), solid-state drives (SSDs) and hard disk drives (HDDs) frequently include hardware-based cache, while web browsers and web servers commonly rely on software caching.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A cache is made up of a pool of entries.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Each entry has associated *data*, which is a copy of the same data in some *backing store*.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Each entry also has a *tag*, which specifies the identity of the data in the backing store of which the entry is a copy.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] When the cache client (a CPU, web browser, operating system) needs to access data presumed to exist in the backing store, it first checks the cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] If an entry can be found with a tag matching that of the desired data, the data in the entry is used instead.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] This situation is known as a **cache hit**.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] For example, a web browser program might check its local cache on disk to see if it has a local copy of the contents of a web page at a particular URL.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In this example, the URL is the tag, and the content of the web page is the data.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The percentage of accesses that result in cache hits is known as the **hit rate** or **hit ratio** of the cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The alternative situation, when the cache is checked and found not to contain any entry with the desired tag, is known as a **cache miss**.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] This requires a more expensive access of data from the backing store.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Once the requested data is retrieved, it is typically copied into the cache, ready for the next access.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] During a cache miss, some other previously existing cache entry is typically removed in order to make room for the newly retrieved data.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The heuristic used to select the entry to replace is known as the replacement policy.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] One popular replacement policy, least recently used (LRU), replaces the oldest entry, the entry that was accessed less recently than any other entry.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] More sophisticated caching algorithms also take into account the frequency of use of entries.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Cache writes must eventually be propagated to the backing store.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The timing for this is governed by the *write policy*.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A write-back cache is more complex to implement since it needs to track which of its locations have been written over and mark them as *dirty* for later writing to the backing store.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The data in these locations are written back to the backing store only when they are evicted from the cache, a process referred to as a *lazy write*.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] For this reason, a read miss in a write-back cache may require two memory accesses to the backing store: one to write back the dirty data, and one to retrieve the requested data.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Other policies may also trigger data write-back.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The client may make many changes to data in the cache, and then explicitly notify the cache to write back the data.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Consequently, a decision needs to be made for write misses: whether or not to load the data into the cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Entities other than the cache may change the data in the backing store, in which case the copy in the cache may become out-of-date or *stale*.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Alternatively, when the client updates the data in the cache, copies of that data in other caches will become stale.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Communication protocols between the cache managers that keep the data consistent are associated with cache coherence.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] On a cache read miss, caches with a *demand paging policy* read the minimum amount from the backing store.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A typical demand-paging virtual memory implementation reads one page of virtual memory (often 4 KB) from disk into the disk cache in RAM.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A typical CPU reads a single L2 cache line of 128 bytes from DRAM into the L2 cache, and a single L1 cache line of 64 bytes from the L2 cache into the L1 cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Caches with a prefetch input queue or more general *anticipatory paging policy* go further—they not only read the data requested, but guess that the next chunk or two of data will soon be required, and so prefetch that data into the cache ahead of time.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Anticipatory paging is especially helpful when the backing store has a long latency to read the first chunk and much shorter times to sequentially read the next few chunks, such as disk storage and DRAM.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A few operating systems go further with a loader that always pre-loads the entire executable into RAM.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A few caches go even further, not only pre-loading an entire file, but also starting to load other related files that may soon be requested, such as the page cache associated with a prefetcher or the web cache associated with link prefetching.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Small memories on or close to the CPU can operate faster than the much larger main memory.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Most CPUs since the 1980s have used one or more caches, sometimes in cascaded levels; modern high-end embedded, desktop and server microprocessors may have as many as six types of cache (between levels and functions).
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Some examples of caches with a specific function are the D-cache, I-cache and the translation lookaside buffer for the memory management unit (MMU).
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Earlier graphics processing units (GPUs) often had limited read-only texture caches and used swizzling to improve 2D locality of reference.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Cache misses would drastically affect performance, e.g. if mipmapping was not used.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Caching was important to leverage 32-bit (and wider) transfers for texture data that was often as little as 4 bits per pixel.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] As GPUs advanced, supporting general-purpose computing on graphics processing units and compute kernels, they have developed progressively larger and increasingly general caches, including instruction caches for shaders, exhibiting functionality commonly found in CPU caches.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] These caches have grown to handle synchronization primitives between threads and atomic operations, and interface with a CPU-style MMU.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Digital signal processors have similarly generalized over the years.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Earlier designs used scratchpad memory fed by direct memory access; modern DSPs often include a very similar set of caches to a CPU (e.g.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Modified Harvard architecture with shared L2, split L1 I-cache and D-cache).
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A memory management unit (MMU) that fetches page table entries from main memory has a specialized cache, used for recording the results of virtual address to physical address translations.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] This specialized cache is called a translation lookaside buffer (TLB).
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Information-centric networking (ICN) is an approach to evolve the Internet infrastructure away from a host-centric paradigm, based on perpetual connectivity and the end-to-end principle, to a network architecture in which the focal point is identified information.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Due to the inherent caching capability of the nodes in an ICN, it can be viewed as a loosely connected network of caches, which has unique requirements for caching policies.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] However, ubiquitous content caching introduces the challenge to content protection against unauthorized access, which requires extra care and solutions.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Unlike proxy servers, in ICN the cache is a network-level solution.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Therefore, it has rapidly changing cache states and higher request arrival rates; moreover, smaller cache sizes impose different requirements on the content eviction policies.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In particular, eviction policies for ICN should be fast and lightweight.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Various cache replication and eviction schemes for different ICN architectures and applications have been proposed.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The time aware least recently used (TLRU) is a variant of LRU designed for the situation where the stored contents in cache have a valid lifetime.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The algorithm is suitable in network cache applications, such as ICN, content delivery networks (CDNs) and distributed networks in general.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] TLRU introduces a new term: time to use (TTU).
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] TTU is a time stamp on content which stipulates the usability time for the content based on the locality of the content and information from the content publisher.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Owing to this locality-based time stamp, TTU provides more control to the local administrator to regulate in-network storage.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In the TLRU algorithm, when a piece of content arrives, a cache node calculates the local TTU value based on the TTU value assigned by the content publisher.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The local TTU value is calculated by using a locally defined function.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Once the local TTU value is calculated the replacement of content is performed on a subset of the total content stored in cache node.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The TLRU ensures that less popular and short-lived content should be replaced with incoming content.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The least frequent recently used (LFRU) cache replacement scheme combines the benefits of LFU and LRU schemes.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] LFRU is suitable for network cache applications, such as ICN, CDNs and distributed networks in general.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In LFRU, the cache is divided into two partitions called privileged and unprivileged partitions.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The privileged partition can be seen as a protected partition.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] If content is highly popular, it is pushed into the privileged partition.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Replacement of the privileged partition is done by first evicting content from the unprivileged partition, then pushing content from the privileged partition to the unprivileged partition, and finally inserting new content into the privileged partition.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In the above procedure, the LRU is used for the privileged partition and an approximated LFU (ALFU) scheme is used for the unprivileged partition.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The basic idea is to cache the locally popular content with the ALFU scheme and push the popular content to the privileged partition.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] In 2011, the use of smartphones with weather forecasting options was overly taxing AccuWeather servers; two requests from the same area would generate separate requests.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] An optimization by edge-servers to truncate the GPS coordinates to fewer decimal places meant that the cached results from a nearby query would be used.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The number of to-the-server lookups per day dropped by half.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] While CPU caches are generally managed entirely by hardware, a variety of software manages other caches.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The page cache in main memory is managed by the operating system kernel.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] While the disk buffer, which is an integrated part of the hard disk drive or solid state drive, is sometimes misleadingly referred to as *disk cache*, its main functions are write sequencing and read prefetching.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] High-end disk controllers often have their own on-board cache for the hard disk drive's data blocks.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Finally, a fast local hard disk drive can also cache information held on even slower data storage devices, such as remote servers (web cache) or local tape drives or optical jukeboxes; such a scheme is the main concept of hierarchical storage management.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Also, fast flash-based solid-state drives (SSDs) can be used as caches for slower rotational-media hard disk drives, working together as hybrid drives.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Web browsers and web proxy servers, either locally or at the Internet service provider (ISP), employ web caches to store previous responses from web servers, such as web pages and images.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Web caches reduce the amount of information that needs to be transmitted across the network, as information previously stored in the cache can often be re-used.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] This reduces bandwidth and processing requirements of the web server, and helps to improve responsiveness for users of the web.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Another form of cache is P2P caching, where the files most sought for by peer-to-peer applications are stored in an ISP cache to accelerate P2P transfers.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Similarly, decentralised equivalents exist, which allow communities to perform the same task for P2P traffic, for example, Corelli.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A cache can store data that is computed on demand rather than retrieved from a backing store.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Memoization is an optimization technique that stores the results of resource-consuming function calls within a lookup table, allowing subsequent calls to reuse the stored results and avoid repeated computation.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] It is related to the dynamic programming algorithm design methodology, which can also be thought of as a means of caching.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A content delivery network (CDN) is a network of distributed servers that deliver pages and other web content to a user, based on the geographic locations of the user, the origin of the web page and the content delivery server.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] CDNs were introduced in the late 1990s as a way to speed up the delivery of static content, such as HTML pages, images and videos.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] By replicating content on multiple servers around the world and delivering it to users based on their location, CDNs can significantly improve the speed and availability of a website or application.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] When a user requests a piece of content, the CDN will check to see if it has a copy of the content in its cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] If it does, the CDN will deliver the content to the user from the cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A cloud storage gateway is a hybrid cloud storage device that connects a local network to one or more cloud storage services, typically object storage services such as Amazon S3.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] It provides a cache for frequently accessed data, providing high speed local access to frequently accessed data in the cloud storage service.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Cloud storage gateways also provide additional benefits such as accessing cloud object storage through traditional file serving protocols as well as continued access to cached data during connectivity outages.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A DNS cache caches a mapping of domain names to IP addresses.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Examples of services providing such caches include the BIND daemon and caching DNS resolver libraries.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Write-through operation is common when operating over unreliable networks, because of the enormous complexity of the coherency protocol required between multiple write-back caches when communication is unreliable.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] For instance, web page caches and client-side caches for distributed file systems (like those in NFS or SMB) are typically read-only or write-through specifically to keep the network protocol simple and reliable.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Web search engines also frequently make web pages they have indexed available from their cache.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] This can prove useful when web pages from a web server are temporarily or permanently inaccessible.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Database caching can substantially improve the throughput of database applications, for example in the processing of indexes, data dictionaries, and frequently used subsets of data.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A distributed cache uses networked hosts to provide scalability, reliability and performance to the application.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The hosts can be co-located or spread over different geographical regions.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Android Runtime and Common Language Runtime are examples that utilize storage-based JIT caches.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] GPU drivers usually utilize storage-based shader caches.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] The semantics of a *buffer* and a *cache* are not totally different; even so, there are fundamental differences in intent between the process of caching and the process of buffering.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Fundamentally, caching realizes a performance increase for transfers of data that is being repeatedly transferred.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] With read caches, a data item must have been fetched from its residing location at least once in order for subsequent reads of the data item to realize a performance increase by virtue of being able to be fetched from the cache's faster intermediate storage rather than the data's residing location.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Contrary to strict buffering, a caching process must adhere to a potentially distributed cache coherency protocol in order to maintain consistency between the cache's intermediate storage and the location where the data resides.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Buffering, on the other hand, reduces the number of transfers for otherwise novel data amongst communicating processes, which amortizes the overhead involved for several small transfers over fewer, larger transfers.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] It also provides an intermediary for communicating processes that are incapable of direct transfers amongst each other, or ensures a minimum data size or representation required by at least one of the communicating processes involved in a transfer.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] With typical caching implementations, a data item that is read or written for the first time is effectively being buffered.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Caching almost always involves some form of buffering, while strict buffering does not necessarily involve caching.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A buffer is a temporary memory location that is traditionally used because CPU instructions cannot directly address data stored in peripheral devices.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Thus, addressable memory is used as an intermediate stage.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Additionally, such a buffer may be required when a large block of data is assembled or disassembled (as required by a storage device), or when data may be delivered in a different order than that in which it is produced.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Also, a whole buffer of data is usually transferred sequentially (for example, to hard disk), so buffering itself sometimes increases transfer performance or reduces the variation or jitter of the transfer's latency as opposed to caching where the intent is to reduce the latency.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] These benefits are present even if the buffered data are written to the buffer once and read from the buffer once.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A cache also increases transfer performance.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A part of the increase similarly comes from the possibility that multiple small transfers will be combined into one large transfer.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] But the main performance gain occurs because there is a good chance that the same data will be read from cache multiple times, or that written data will soon be read.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] A cache's sole purpose is to reduce accesses to the underlying slower storage.
[src:azure-cdn/cache-computing] Cache is also usually an abstraction layer that is designed to be invisible from the perspective of neighboring layers.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] A **content delivery network** (**CDN**) or **content distribution network** is a geographically distributed network of proxy servers and corresponding data centers.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDNs provide high availability and performance ("speed") through geographical distribution relative to end users, and arose in the late 1990s to alleviate the performance bottlenecks of the Internet as it was becoming a critical medium.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Since then, CDNs have grown to serve a large portion of Internet content, including text, graphics and scripts, downloadable objects (media files, software, and documents), applications (e-commerce, portals), live streaming media, on-demand streaming media, and social media services.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDNs are a layer in the internet ecosystem.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Content owners such as media companies and e-commerce vendors pay CDN operators to deliver their content to their end users.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In turn, a CDN pays Internet service providers (ISPs), carriers, and network operators for hosting its servers in their data centers.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDN vendors may cross over into other industries like security, DDoS protection and web application firewalls (WAF), and WAN optimization.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Content delivery service providers include Akamai Technologies, Cloudflare, Amazon CloudFront, Qwilt (Cisco), Fastly, CDN77, BunnyCDN, EdgeNext, and Google Cloud CDN.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDN nodes are usually deployed in multiple locations, often over multiple Internet backbones.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Benefits include reducing bandwidth costs, improving page load times, and increasing the global availability of content.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The number of nodes and servers making up a CDN varies, depending on the architecture, some reaching thousands of nodes with tens of thousands of servers on many remote points of presence (PoPs).
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Others build a global network and have a small number of geographical PoPs.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Requests for content are typically algorithmically directed to nodes that are optimal in some way.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for performance, locations that are best for serving content to the user may be chosen.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This may be measured by choosing locations that are the fewest hops or the shortest time to the requesting client, or the highest server performance, to optimize delivery across local networks.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] When optimizing for cost, locations that are the least expensive may be chosen instead.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In an optimal scenario, these two goals tend to align, as **edge servers** that are close to the end user at the edge of the network may have an advantage in performance and cost.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Most CDN providers will provide their services over a varying, defined, set of PoPs, depending on the coverage desired, such as United States, Asia-Pacific, International or Global, etc.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] These sets of PoPs can be called "edges", "edge nodes", "edge servers", or "edge networks" as they would be the closest edge of CDN assets to the end user.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDN providers profit either from direct fees paid by content providers using their network, or profit from the user analytics and tracking data collected as their scripts are being loaded onto customers' websites inside their browser origin.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] As such these services are being pointed out as potential privacy intrusions for the purpose of behavioral targeting and solutions are being created to restore single-origin serving and caching of resources.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In particular, a website using a CDN may violate the EU's General Data Protection Regulation (GDPR).
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] For example, in 2021 a German court forbade the use of a CDN on a university website, because this caused the transmission of the user's IP address to the CDN, which violated the GDPR.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDNs serving JavaScript have also been targeted as a way to inject malicious content into pages using them.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Subresource Integrity mechanism was created in response to ensure that the page loads a script whose content is known and constrained to a hash referenced by the website author.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The Internet was designed according to the end-to-end principle.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This principle keeps the core network relatively simple and moves the intelligence as much as possible to the network end-points: the hosts and clients.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] As a result, the core network is specialized, optimized, and simplified to only forward data packets.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Content Delivery Networks extend the transport network by distributing on it a variety of intelligent applications employing techniques designed to optimize content delivery.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The resulting tightly integrated overlay uses web caching, server-load balancing, request routing, and content services.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Web caches store popular content on servers that have the greatest demand for the content requested.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] These shared network appliances reduce bandwidth requirements, reduce server load, and improve the client response times for content stored in the cache.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Web caches are populated based on requests from users (pull caching) or based on preloaded content disseminated from content servers (push caching).
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Server-load balancing uses one or more techniques including service-based (global load balancing) or hardware-based (i.e. layer 4–7 switches, also known as a web switch, content switch, or multilayer switch) to share traffic among a number of servers or web caches.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Here the switch is assigned a single virtual IP address.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Traffic arriving at the switch is then directed to one of the real web servers attached to the switch.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This has the advantage of balancing load, increasing total capacity, improving scalability, and providing increased reliability by redistributing the load of a failed web server and providing server health checks.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] A content cluster or service node can be formed using a layer 4–7 switch to balance load across a number of servers or a number of web caches within the network.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Request routing directs client requests to the content source best able to serve the request.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This may involve directing a client request to the service node that is closest to the client, or to the one with the most capacity.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] A variety of algorithms are used to route the request.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] These include Global Server Load Balancing, DNS-based request routing, Dynamic metafile generation, HTML rewriting, and anycasting.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Proximity—choosing the closest service node—is estimated using a variety of techniques including reactive probing, proactive probing, and connection monitoring.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDNs use a variety of methods of content delivery including, but not limited to, manual asset copying, active web caches, and global hardware load balancers.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Several protocol suites are designed to provide access to a wide variety of content services distributed throughout a content network.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The Internet Content Adaptation Protocol (ICAP) was developed in the late 1990s to provide an open standard for connecting application servers.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] A more recently defined and robust solution is provided by the Open Pluggable Edge Services (OPES) protocol.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This architecture defines OPES service applications that can reside on the OPES processor itself or be executed remotely on a Callout Server.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Edge Side Includes or ESI is a small markup language for edge-level dynamic web content assembly.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] It is fairly common for websites to have generated content.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] It could be because of changing content like catalogs or forums, or because of the personalization.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This creates a problem for caching systems.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] To overcome this problem, a group of companies created ESI.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In *peer-to-peer (P2P)* content-delivery networks, clients provide resources as well as use them.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This means that, unlike client–server systems, the content-centric networks can actually perform better as more users begin to access the content (especially with protocols such as Bittorrent that require users to share).
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This property is one of the major advantages of using P2P networks because it makes the setup and running costs very small for the original content distributor.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] To incentive peers to participate in the P2P network, web3 and blockchain technologies can be used: participating nodes receive crypto tokens in exchange of their involvement.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] If content owners are not satisfied with the options or costs of a commercial CDN service, they can create their own CDN.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] A private CDN consists of PoPs (points of presence) that are only serving content for their owner.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] These PoPs can be caching servers, reverse proxies or application delivery controllers.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] It can be as simple as two caching servers, or large enough to serve petabytes of content.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] When a private CDN is deployed within a company network, it is also referred as Entreprise CDN or **eCDN**.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Large content distribution networks may even build and set up their own private network to distribute copies of content across cache locations.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Such private networks are usually used in conjunction with public networks as a backup option in case the capacity of the private network is not enough or there is a failure which leads to capacity reduction.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Since the same content has to be distributed across many locations, a variety of multicasting techniques may be used to reduce bandwidth consumption.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Over private networks, it has also been proposed to select multicast trees according to network load conditions to more efficiently utilize available network capacity.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The rapid growth of streaming video traffic required large capital expenditures by broadband providers in order to meet this demand and retain subscribers by delivering a sufficiently good quality of experience.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] To address this, telecommunications service providers have begun to launch their own content delivery networks as a means to lessen the demands on the network backbone and reduce infrastructure investments.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Because they own the networks over which video content is transmitted, telco CDNs have advantages over traditional CDNs.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] They own the last mile and can deliver content closer to the end-user because it can be cached deep in their networks.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This deep caching minimizes the distance that video data travels over the general Internet and delivers it more quickly and reliably.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Telco CDNs also have a built-in cost advantage since traditional CDNs must lease bandwidth from them and build the operator's margin into their own cost model.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In addition, by operating their own content delivery infrastructure, telco operators have better control over the utilization of their resources.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Content management operations performed by CDNs are usually applied without (or with very limited) information about the network (e.g., topology, utilization etc.) of the telco-operators with which they interact or have business relationships.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] These pose a number of challenges for the telco-operators who have a limited sphere of action in face of the impact of these operations on the utilization of their resources.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In contrast, the deployment of telco-CDNs allows operators to implement their own content management operations, which enables them to have a better control over the utilization of their resources and, as such, provide better quality of service and experience to their end users.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In June 2011, StreamingMedia.com reported that a group of TSPs had founded an Operator Carrier Exchange (OCX) to interconnect their networks and compete more directly against large traditional CDNs like Akamai and Limelight Networks, which have extensive PoPs worldwide.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This way, telcos are building a Federated CDN offering, which is more interesting for a content provider willing to deliver its content to the aggregated audience of this federation.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] It is likely that in a near future, other telco CDN federations will be created.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] They will grow by enrollment of new telcos joining the federation and bringing network presence and their Internet subscriber bases to the existing ones.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The Open Caching specification by Streaming Video Technology Alliance defines a set of APIs that allows a Content Provider to deliver its content using several CDNs in a consistent way, seeing each CDN provider the same way through these APIs.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Combining several CDN services allow Content Providers to not rely on a single CDN service, especially concerned to deal with high peak audience during live events.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] There are several ways to allocate traffic to a particular CDN among the list, either client-side CDN selection, or server-side (at the Content Provider's origin) or cloud-side (in the middle, between the content origin and the audience).
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] CDN selection criteria can be performance, availability and cost.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Traditionally, CDNs have used the IP of the client's recursive DNS resolver to geo-locate the client.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] While this is a sound approach in many situations, this leads to poor client performance if the client uses a non-local recursive DNS resolver that is far away.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] For instance, a CDN may route requests from a client in India to its edge server in Singapore, if that client uses a public DNS resolver in Singapore, causing poor performance for that client.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Indeed, a recent study showed that in many countries where public DNS resolvers are in popular use, the median distance between the clients and their recursive DNS resolvers can be as high as a thousand miles.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In August 2011, a global consortium of leading Internet service providers led by Google announced their official implementation of the edns-client-subnet IETF Internet Draft, which is intended to accurately localize DNS resolution responses.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The initiative involves a limited number of leading DNS service providers, such as Google Public DNS, and CDN service providers as well.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] With the edns-client-subnet EDNS0 option, CDNs can now utilize the IP address of the requesting client's subnet when resolving DNS requests.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] This approach, called end-user mapping, has been adopted by CDNs and it has been shown to drastically reduce the round-trip latencies and improve performance for clients who use public DNS or other non-local resolvers.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] However, the use of EDNS0 also has drawbacks as it decreases the effectiveness of caching resolutions at the recursive resolvers, increases the total DNS resolution traffic, and raises a privacy concern of exposing the client's subnet.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Virtualization technologies are being used to deploy virtual CDNs (vCDNs) (also known as a software-defined CDN or sd-CDN) with the goal to reduce content provider costs, and at the same time, increase elasticity and decrease service delay.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] With vCDNs, it is possible to avoid traditional CDN limitations, such as performance, reliability and availability since virtual caches are deployed dynamically (as virtual machines or containers) in physical servers distributed across the provider's geographical coverage.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] As the virtual cache placement is based on both the content type and server or end-user geographic location, the vCDNs have a significant impact on service delivery and network congestion.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] To boost performance, delivery to clients from servers can use alternate non-HTTP protocols such as WebRTC and WebSockets.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] In 2017, Addy Osmani of Google started referring to software solutions that could integrate naturally with the Responsive Web Design paradigm (with particular reference to the <picture> element) as **Image CDN**s.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The expression referred to the ability of a web architecture to serve multiple versions of the same image through HTTP, depending on the properties of the browser requesting it, as determined by either the browser or the server-side logic.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] The purpose of Image CDNs was, in Google's vision, to serve high-quality images (or, better, images perceived as high-quality by the human eye) while preserving download speed, thus contributing to a great User experience (UX).
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Arguably, the *Image CDN* term was originally a misnomer, as neither Cloudinary nor Imgix (the examples quoted by Google in the 2017 guide by Addy Osmani) were, at the time, a CDN in the classical sense of the term.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Shortly afterwards, though, several companies offered solutions that allowed developers to serve different versions of their graphical assets according to several strategies.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] Many of these solutions were built on top of traditional CDNs, such as Akamai, CloudFront, Fastly, Edgecast and Cloudflare.
[src:azure-cdn/content-delivery-network] At the same time, other solutions that already provided an image multi-serving service joined the Image CDN definition by either offering CDN functionality natively (ImageEngine) or integrating with one of the existing CDNs (Cloudinary/Akamai, Imgix/Fastly).
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] The term began being used in the 1990s to describe content delivery networks—these were used to deliver website and video content from servers located near users.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] In the early 2000s, these systems expanded their scope to hosting other applications, leading to early edge computing services.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] These services could do things like find dealers, manage shopping carts, gather real-time data, and place ads.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] The Internet of things (IoT), where devices are connected to the Internet, is often linked with edge computing.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Edge computing involves running computer programs that deliver quick responses close to where requests are made.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Karim Arabi, during an IEEE DAC 2014 keynote and later at an MIT MTL Seminar in 2015, described edge computing as computing that occurs outside the cloud, at the network's edge, particularly for applications needing immediate data processing.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Edge computing is often equated with fog computing, particularly in smaller setups.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] However, in larger deployments, such as smart cities, fog computing serves as a distinct layer between edge computing and cloud computing, with each layer having its own responsibilities.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] "The State of the Edge" report explains that edge computing focuses on servers located close to the end-users.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Alex Reznik, Chair of the ETSI MEC ISG standards committee, defines 'edge' loosely as anything that's not a traditional data center.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] In cloud gaming, edge nodes, known as "gamelets", are typically within one or two network hops from the client, ensuring quick response times for real-time games.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Edge computing might use virtualization technology to simplify deploying and managing various applications on edge servers.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] In 2018, the world's data was expected to grow 61 percent to 175 zettabytes by 2025.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] According to research firm Gartner, around 10 percent of enterprise-generated data is created and processed outside a traditional centralized data center or cloud.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] By 2025, the firm predicts that this figure will reach 75 percent.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] The increase in IoT devices at the edge of the network is producing a massive amount of data — storing and using all that data in cloud data centers pushes network bandwidth requirements to the limit.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Despite the improvements in network technology, data centers cannot guarantee acceptable transfer rates and response times, which often is a critical requirement for many applications.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Furthermore, devices at the edge constantly consume data coming from the cloud, forcing companies to decentralize data storage and service provisioning, leveraging physical proximity to the end user.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] In a similar way, the aim of edge computing is to move the computation away from data centers towards the edge of the network, exploiting smart objects, mobile phones, or network gateways to perform tasks and provide services on behalf of the cloud.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] By moving services to the edge, it is possible to provide content caching, service delivery, persistent data storage, and IoT management resulting in better response times and transfer rates.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] At the same time, distributing the logic to different network nodes introduces new issues and challenges.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] The distributed nature of this paradigm introduces a shift in security schemes used in cloud computing.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] In edge computing, data may travel between different distributed nodes connected via the internet, and thus requires special encryption mechanisms independent of the cloud.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] This approach minimizes latency, reduces bandwidth consumption, and enhances real-time responsiveness for applications.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Edge nodes may also be resource-constrained devices, limiting the choice in terms of security methods.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Moreover, a shift from centralized top-down infrastructure to a decentralized trust model is required.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] On the other hand, by keeping and processing data at the edge, it is possible to increase privacy by minimizing the transmission of sensitive information to the cloud.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Furthermore, the ownership of collected data shifts from service providers to end-users.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Scalability in a distributed network must face different issues.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] First, it must take into account the heterogeneity of the devices, having different performance and energy constraints, the highly dynamic condition, and the reliability of the connections compared to more robust infrastructure of cloud data centers.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Moreover, security requirements may introduce further latency in the communication between nodes, which may slow down the scaling process.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] The state-of-the-art scheduling technique can increase the effective utilization of edge resources and scales the edge server by assigning minimum edge resources to each offloaded task.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Management of failovers is crucial in order to keep a service alive.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] If a single node goes down and is unreachable, users should still be able to access a service without interruptions.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Moreover, edge computing systems must provide actions to recover from a failure and alert the user about the incident.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] To this aim, each device must maintain the network topology of the entire distributed system, so that detection of errors and recovery become easily applicable.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Other factors that may influence this aspect are the connection technologies in use, which may provide different levels of reliability, and the accuracy of the data produced at the edge that could be unreliable due to particular environment conditions.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] As an example, an edge computing device, such as a voice assistant, may continue to provide service to local users even during cloud service or internet outages.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Edge computing brings analytical computational resources close to the end users and therefore can increase the responsiveness and throughput of applications.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] A well-designed edge platform would significantly outperform a traditional cloud-based system.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Some applications rely on short response times, making edge computing a significantly more feasible option than cloud computing.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Examples range from IoT to autonomous driving, anything health or human / public safety relevant, or involving human perception such as facial recognition, which typically takes a human between 370-620 ms to perform.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Edge computing is more likely to be able to mimic the same perception speed as humans, which is useful in applications such as augmented reality, where the headset should preferably recognize who a person is at the same time as the wearer does.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Due to the nearness of the analytical resources to the end users, sophisticated analytical tools and artificial intelligence tools can run on the edge of the system.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] This placement at the edge helps to increase operational efficiency and is responsible for many advantages to the system.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] In distributed AI systems on the edge, data compression is increasingly recognized as a foundational design layer to mitigate bandwidth constraints caused by the exchange of large models and high-resolution sensor streams.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] By using servers located on a local edge network to perform those computations, the video files only need to be transmitted in the local network.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Avoiding transmission over the internet results in significant bandwidth savings and therefore increases efficiency.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] If the recognition is performed locally, it is possible to send the recognized text to the cloud rather than audio recordings, significantly reducing the amount of required bandwidth.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Edge application services reduce the volumes of data that must be moved, the consequent traffic, and the distance that data must travel.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] That provides lower latency and reduces transmission costs.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Computation offloading for real-time applications, such as facial recognition algorithms, showed considerable improvements in response times, as demonstrated in early research.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Further research showed that using resource-rich machines called cloudlets or micro data centers near mobile users, which offer services typically found in the cloud, provided improvements in execution time when some of the tasks are offloaded to the edge node.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] On the other hand, offloading every task may result in a slowdown due to transfer times between device and nodes, so depending on the workload, an optimal configuration can be defined.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] An IoT-based power grid system enables communication of electricity and data to monitor and control the power grid, which makes energy management more efficient.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] Other notable applications include connected cars, self-driving cars, smart cities, Industry 4.0, home automation, missiles,, satellite systems , as well as frameworks such as MediaPipe.
[src:azure-cdn/edge-computing] The growing field of **edge artificial intelligence** (edge AI or edge intelligence, sometimes referred to as "local AI" or "on-device AI") implements artificial intelligence in an edge computing environment, on the device or close to where data is collected.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] A **web cache** (or **HTTP cache**) is a system for optimizing the World Wide Web.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] It is implemented both client-side and server-side.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] The caching of multimedia and other files can result in less overall delay when browsing the Web.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] A forward cache is a cache outside the web server's network, e.g. in the client's web browser, in an Internet service provider, or within a corporate network.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] A network-aware forward cache only caches heavily accessed items.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] A proxy server sitting between the client and web server can evaluate HTTP headers and choose whether to store web content.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] A reverse cache sits in front of one or more web servers, accelerating requests from the Internet and reducing peak server load.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] This is usually a content delivery network (CDN) that retains copies of web content at various points throughout a network.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] The Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP) defines three basic mechanisms for controlling caches: freshness, validation, and invalidation.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] This is specified in the header of HTTP response messages from the server.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] Freshness allows a response to be used without re-checking it on the origin server, and can be controlled by both the server and the client.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] For example, the Expires response header gives a date when the document becomes stale, and the Cache-Control: max-age directive tells the cache how many seconds the response is fresh for.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] Validation can be used to check whether a cached response is still good after it becomes stale.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] For example, if the response has a Last-Modified header, a cache can make a *conditional request* using the If-Modified-Since header to see if it has changed.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] The ETag (entity tag) mechanism also allows for both strong and weak validation.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] Invalidation is usually a side effect of another request that passes through the cache.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] For example, if a URL associated with a cached response subsequently gets a POST, PUT or DELETE request, the cached response will be invalidated.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] Many CDNs and manufacturers of network equipment have replaced this standard HTTP cache control with dynamic caching.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] In 1998, the Digital Millennium Copyright Act added rules to the United States Code (17 U.S.C. §: 512) that exempts system operators from copyright liability for the purposes of caching.
[src:azure-cdn/http-caching] This is a list of server-side web caching software.
[src:azure-cdn/point-of-presence] A **point of presence** (**PoP**) is an artificial demarcation point or network interface point between communicating entities.
[src:azure-cdn/point-of-presence] A common example is an **ISP point of presence**, the local access point that allows users to connect to the Internet with their Internet service provider (ISP).
[src:azure-cdn/point-of-presence] A PoP typically houses servers, routers, network switches, multiplexers, and other network interface equipment that connects an ISP to customers including OLTs (optical line terminals) for fibre internet, and is typically located in a data center.
[src:azure-cdn/point-of-presence] PoPs are often located at Internet exchange points and colocation centers.
[src:azure-cdn/point-of-presence] In the US, this term became important during the court-ordered breakup of the Bell Telephone system.
[src:azure-cdn/point-of-presence] A point of presence was a location where a long-distance carrier (IXC) could terminate services and provide connections into a local telephone network (LATA).
